The Alchemist's guide for humanity goes as such: Decentralization the ethos. Let the imitates find logic and lead with intuition. One line of code unlocks the secrets to the Blockchain. Freedom of speech and the freedom to explain oneself before the masses gather to burn an individual at the stake. Knowledge>Charisma. Always, never forget that, and do not be seduced by language, for you will be lost. Worship the prime number and the elliptical curves that you find, they are to be revered. Respect, always treat your fellow human with respect, or risk losing your integrity within the community. One last tiny caveat, have a sense of humor. Alchemists are always busy working so it is best not to be uptight as hard as that may be in this day and age. These are unofficial rules that I made up last night. Just something to think about you dig.

crud 10-Mar-21 09:02 AM
that is also what I was thinking about, but honestly I didn't really made any reading on Alchemy symbols and stuff until yesterday. Good part is that there are decent amount of information. Once you know what you want and create a symbol set you can apply a procedural generation algorithm to a unique key and get bunch of cool looking images and use them on NFT's the tricky part is the meaning. I don't really see any value on randomly slapping symbols when we can do a lot better. This definitely would complicate things quite a lot but imho. it worth a try. Another suggestion on my end would be to get in touch with some sort of an expert (or a knowledgeable hobbyist) in this topic to explain how it is structured and what does all symbols/lines/shapes mean b/c I have seen many different definitions. an another idea would be to create our own vocabulary? my thought process is that alchemy is and has been practiced like for thousands of years. One thing in common was the chemistry. Basically the aim was to transmutate an element (or set of elements) into another (gold was mostly the aim) therefore it was also mostly focused on metal elements ...etc. What we have here is a context change from physical world of metals, stones, elements to digital world of bytes and numbers. basically we are not in the physical world anymore so our goal with the transmutation is also different than what the old generation of alchemists did. Therefore we need our own set of vocabulary that we can use on top of the system created by elders What I also really loved is the tradition. Basically the fact that alchemical symbols are all over the place throughout the history, especially churches and art. Since it was forbidden and people had to hide they always had to hide/cover their knowledge in disguise in order to pass it to next generation. So imho. easter eggs is a must

Alchemy in Jacob Boehme‚Äôs Theosophy | Down the Rabbit Hole
11:34
During the Early Modern Period the world was undergoing a major transition from a geocentric to a heliocentric cosmogony; from an occult and animistic landscape to a mechanistic and reductionist one defined by mechanistic processes that operated independently of any conscious and creative force. The indeterminate space left vacant between Copernican limelight and the Newtonian sunrise was quickly filled by the speculative and metaphysical vision of Jacob Boehme (1575-1624), a German cobbler who integrated streams of Hermetic, Renaissance Neo-platonic, alchemical, mystical, Christian, and early scientific thought to create a Weltanschauung (a comprehensive view of the world)

Red0x 12-Mar-21 04:03 AM
Release 3 digital items with some scarce supply for each. Imagine the amount of LP staked corresponds to the bracket of item you could unlock/claim... The rarest item only has 50 units for example and requires a large amount of LP staked... 2nd item 500 with less LP staked and 3rd item 2,500 with even less staked... in order to claim the item you have to stake for some minimum amount of time. (3 months or 6 months?) Since there would be a limited number of items it would incentivize people to stake earlier so that they could get over the time requirement and claim the item before they all run out. Once they run out you could reset with new items. (edited)
Red0x 12-Mar-21 04:12 AM

That is the story of our hero that found the key to unlock the full potential to humanity. crud 14-Mar-21 08:54 PM
well, I've just uploaded it to the basecamp/nft section as RFC but also re-posting it here. After playing around with some symbols & rings I've realized that I am quite amazed by old drawings and books that I could find and wanted to replicate it somehow. Basically I always wanted to go with the Old Manuscript theme but decided to draw some potions instead of rings hoping it might fit better into book of crucibles I made here -> https://alchemy-book.vercel.app but things can change as time passes, we'll see Anyways, this is the first iteration of my first generative NFT art try after a 1.5 days of playing around. Currently all of the potions you see have been generated from different seeds. The variations are quite restricted rn. but it will increase as the code grows, all of the drawings are done using js so you can imagine there is some math and figuring shit out involved Given my time constraint I wouldn't expect any big updates until next weekend. my probable next steps are: - create multiple cork styles - create multiple bottle styles (n-gon, sphere...etc.) - assign classes (fire, earth, wind ...etc.) - create a symbol<->meaning mapping - add generated symbols to the paper depending on the class. probably not possible for hackathon: - generate the a text as well? - potion holder? - potion body symbols and drawings (patterns) - potion neck clothing & symbols I'd love to hear your thoughts, suggestions & criticisms. cheers
SPOILER

NamaCitta 14-Mar-21 11:41 PM
Also, I'm not a developer/coder, so I'm not at all fluent in how smart contracts actually work, but is there a way to have NFT's "recognize" each other so having a certain number or combination of different NFTs in a wallet can affect other multipliers or yield or enhance probability of generating other specific types of NFT design? For example, if we were able to have one crucible classed as "Earth" and another classed as "Air", would smart contracts be able to recognize having both to allow minting of a third different kind of NFT? Is it possible to bake into the tokenomics and the mechanics of minting a way to kind of replicate the actual Alchemical process of combining specifice "elements" of NFTs to creat others? That might enhance value of certain NFT crucibles and expand the mythology and fun of the project? Or if we eventually have other LP pairs, one crucible with Mist/Eth in the same wallet as a Crucible with Mist/[other token] allows minting of a third different NFT/Crucible (theoretically the result of having the other two). Maybe this is all too much, but what if...? (edited)

Fiddlekins 19-Mar-21 08:44 PM
Open to all, but a traditional artist will struggle to produce something that meets the full specification. I'm not too sure how it's judged, but I wouldn't be surprised if a good piece of artwork, with details on how it could be varied based on ID etc, could win one of the runner up awards. Having said that, the general recommendation is that people team up to pool their skillsets to deliver a complete solution. eg. One guy can code, but can't art. Another guy can art, but can't code. Together they can produce a program that creates nice art based on ID.

crud 29-Mar-21 07:15 PM
Greetings, I've posted an another update on the basecamp > NFT > potions > v2 directory that I have created previously, waiting for your comments I will also post a couple of images here in case you don't get notified on the basecamp. basically there has been some iterations since the last update, I've seen that we, as a community were quite interested in displaying dynamic data on the nft so I came up with following to display the data: I wanted to figure out a way to encode the data (age, the stake, amount of rewards ...etc.) without writing any text and I've decided to paint it so I used I've put together an L-tree from examples I find online and extended it so that can grow with time and gives leaves and flowers as the stake and the farm grows additionally I wanted to keep the magical/old drawing type of style I've added some other mathematical patterns and random symbols. currently everything is drawn on the canvas using p5js and the variables are generated from the id (which needs quite some work if we want to try it out with all of the seeds). that gives each tree it's own characteristics in addition to the potion style ...etc. (edited)

Fiddlekins 05-Apr-21 02:58 PM
is it possible from the creation TXN to extract what pair of tokens are locked
You could potentially determine what LP was used during the crucibles creation, but people can add and remove LP after that. It would be better to have a way of checking the current contents of a crucible for that data
My dream is to create NFTs which would inform the user about every single detail on the exact NFT so when people would trade on OpenSea there wouldn't be any confusion.
Definitely a cool idea worth pursuing, but technical limitations might make that impractical in the short term. OpenSea requires static assets to display for its NFTs, eg. an image or a video. As such, for an image or video to represent a crucible, it would need to be recreated whenever the LP contents changed. This might be possible, but it would likely introduce a time delay, so relying on the image to confirm what the crucible contains could be unreliable

Fiddlekins 05-Apr-21 03:03 PM
Also I think i figured out how it would be simple to made 1 million or more unique crucible NFTs
Ideally, every possible crucible would be unique. This would mean that every possible crucible ID would generate art that is different from every other crucible ID. Crucible IDs are the same as their address, which is 2^160 possible combinations. Obviously, this is shared amongst all the other possible smart contracts on the ethereum network, and moreover people won't ever generate anywhere near that number, but it's still important to try to aim for that theoretical number of variations on generated crucible art to ensure that by chance we don't get two that are alike
Borelis 05-Apr-21 03:04 PM
So I guess extracting what tokens are locked inside and where are they locked is also quite difficult or almost impossible to track.
Fiddlekins 05-Apr-21 03:06 PM
is it possible to make it randomize, but not repeating, and can the code extract each number separately?
I've got an example that endeavours to this, though it could probably be improved. It takes a PRNG and seeds it with the crucible ID. In theory, with a different seed the PRNG will output different sequences of random numbers, and thus using them will give you something unique each time. In practise though this relies on how the PRNG behaves, and alas I am no expert on that matter. You can find the code where I set this up here: https://github.com/Fiddlekins/alchemist-crucible-lens/blob/master/src/lens/PRNG.js And how it is used here: https://github.com/Fiddlekins/alchemist-crucible-lens/blob/master/src/components/Crucible.jsx

Fiddlekins 05-Apr-21 03:08 PM
When extracting numbers directly from the ID you have a limited number you can pick before you run out, or have to loop back from the start again, etc
15:09
And moreover it forces you to create variations with fixed ranges - you always need 10 options for a single digit for example
15:09
if you wanted a few more options, you'd have to consume two digits, and now you need to supply 100 options
15:10
It also makes it trickier if you want to adjust how it works later on

NamaCitta 05-Apr-21 05:13 PM
Yeah, that was me So many different interesting artistic presentations, and since I sadly lack those skills (I'm more historical, words, concepts) I was having visions of how to incorporate as many of the different styles as possible into a single unified, organic working system/unit. What I love about the magic circles that I saw folks developing is that visually they are awesome, they trigger and reference all of the mystical circles we've seen in ancient texts, but with some thought we can incorporate Defi metrics into the circles as well as embed some Mytical ongoing project reveals into them. And yes I was thinking the more artistic, paintingl-like submissions that arent 3-D type renders would make excellent reverse-side artworks on the back of the data elements on the other side. I love the idea of crafting a system were we have bits of everyone merged into a single ongoing type of format...[oops I might have replied to the wrong bit of the post...] (edited)

I'm also loving the idea that eventually we could come up with some form of protocol where perhaps we can also expand Alchemist beyond just minting Crucibles to being able to combine NFTs into particular collateralized pools to mint or generate other NFTs. I'm not a coder so I don't have good sense of what is possible, but I was thinking that eventually we would have multiple MIST liquidity pools that could mint particular NFT elements, and those NFT elements could also then be pooled together to mint a further result. from a DeFi point of view its simply more liquidity, etc, but from a coolnes Alchemist point of view then MIST/ETH mints say Mercury NFT, MIST/BTC mints Hopium NFT, and then combine the Mercury and Hopium NFTs in an NFT pool to mint/create something else which moves us along the path of the Stone. I'm just fooling around with ideas but I love the idea that folks could actually be minting actual elements when creating different LP combinations, and then combining the resulting NFTs for further alchemical exploration....

I have always been much more excited about the usefulness case for NFTs rather than just a curio ownership mechanism, kudos to people who like that type of exclusive art but my excitement around NFTs has always been around what neat things they can be used for. I think the 'sole owner of some piece of art' example will have its niche, but I think a lot of hype around NFTs is just consumerism driven with new ways of showing you own something. which is fine and will make a lot of people and companies a lot of money, but I have always been most excited about functionalism.
04:00
my first and favorite NFT I had was back in 2014 some friends of mine made a hosted bitcoin mining service, and they sold shares in that mining service with colored bitcoin (back in the good old days of coinprism before it went out of business) the mined bitcoin profit from the mining rigs were automatically paid out to whoever was the owner of the mining share NFTs, so you could buy/sell mining shares and the mined btc would be automatically sent to whatever bitcoin address had possession of the NFTs, it was such a cool new way to do crypto I had never seen anything like it
